  "prompt": "What should I do if my PayPal account is hacked?",
  "response": "If you suspect that your PayPal account has been hacked, follow these steps immediately:\n\n1. **Change Your Password:**\n   - Log in to your PayPal account (if you can) and change your password to something strong and unique.\n\n2. **Enable Two-Factor Authentication:**\n   - If you haven't already, enable two-factor authentication (2FA) for added security. This requires a second form of verification (like a code sent to your phone) when logging in.\n\n3. **Review Account Activity:**\n   - Check your account for any unauthorized transactions. Make note of any transactions that you do not recognize.\n\n4. **Report Unauthorized Transactions:**\n   - If you see any unauthorized transactions, report them to PayPal through their Resolution Center immediately. You can dispute transactions that you did not authorize.\n\n5. **Contact PayPal Support:**\n   - If you're unable to log in or notice suspicious activity, contact PayPal's customer support directly. You can do this through their help center or by calling them.\n\n6. **Check Your Linked Accounts:**\n   - If your PayPal is connected to your bank account or credit cards, check those accounts for any unauthorized activity as well.\n\n7. **Run Security Software:**\n   - Run a complete scan on your computer for malware or viruses that may have compromised your security.\n\n8. **Update Security Questions:**\n   - Change your security questions and answers to prevent unauthorized access.\n\n9. **Monitor Your Other Accounts:**\n   - Be vigilant about other accounts that may have used the same password or lack of 2FA, and update their security settings as well.\n\n10. **Educate Yourself on Phishing:**\n    - Be cautious of phishing emails or messages that may try to trick you into giving up more personal information. Always verify the source before clicking links or providing information.\n\n11. **Consider Identity Theft Protection:**\n    - If you believe your personal information may be compromised beyond just PayPal, consider enrolling in an identity theft protection service.\n\nTaking these steps can help secure your PayPal account and protect your financial information from further compromise.",
